    <question>
        <prompt>What characterized Woodrow Wilson's attitude toward civil rights?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">He strongly supported racial equality</option>
            <option letter="b">He segregated the federal government</option>
            <option letter="c">He passed anti-discrimination laws</option>
            <option letter="d">He appointed Black cabinet members</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>Wilson actually increased segregation by segregating the federal government workforce, showing his support for Jim Crow policies despite his progressive stance on other issues.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>What was the primary role of the Committee on Public Information?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Gathering military intelligence</option>
            <option letter="b">Creating pro-war propaganda</option>
            <option letter="c">Regulating newspapers</option>
            <option letter="d">Managing food supplies</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>The Committee on Public Information, led by George Creel, created and distributed propaganda to build public support for America's involvement in World War I.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>How did Native Americans fare during this period?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">They gained full citizenship rights</option>
            <option letter="b">They faced forced assimilation</option>
            <option letter="c">They received vast land grants</option>
            <option letter="d">They gained political power</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>Native Americans faced forced assimilation through boarding schools, continued land loss, and weren't granted citizenship until 1924, while enduring various forms of discrimination.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>What was significant about D.W. Griffith's "Birth of a Nation"?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">It promoted racial equality</option>
            <option letter="b">It glorified the KKK</option>
            <option letter="c">It documented the Civil War accurately</option>
            <option letter="d">It was about American independence</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>While technically innovative, "Birth of a Nation" was deeply racist, glorified the KKK, and contributed to its revival, leading to protests by the NAACP and others.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>What was Carrie Chapman Catt's main contribution to women's rights?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">She opposed women's suffrage</option>
            <option letter="b">She led NAWSA to achieve voting rights</option>
            <option letter="c">She focused on prohibition</option>
            <option letter="d">She promoted women in sports</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>Carrie Chapman Catt led the National American Woman Suffrage Association (NAWSA) and developed the successful "Winning Plan" that helped achieve the passage of the 19th Amendment.</explanation>
    </question>
